Masandwana beat the Egyptian giants 3-0 at the Lucas Moripe Stadium on Saturday. JOHANNESBURG &ndash; Mamelodi Sundowns emerge victorious in the hotly contested match against Egypt&rsquo;s Zamalek at the Lucas Moripe Stadium in Pretoria on Saturday. Sundowns won by 3-0 against Zamalek in the first leg of the CAF Champions League final.&nbsp; #CAFCLFinal Not even 1 minute after the break and Sundowns have a goal. An own goal though. Sundowns 3-0 Zamalek after 46 minutes &mdash; EWN Sport (@EWNsport) October 15, 2016 #CAFCLFinal And it's all over! Mamelodi Sundowns take a 3-0 win with them to Egypt! &mdash; EWN Sport (@EWNsport) October 15, 2016 Anthony Blasts conceded the first goal for the local team just over 30 minutes from the starting whistle, and that was followed by a second from Tebogo Langerman minutes before half-time. #CAFCLFinal Langerman tries another shot from range. Sundowns have Zamalek rattled here. 2-0 after 42 minutes. &mdash; EWN Sport (@EWNsport) October 15, 2016 Ref calls time on an action packed half! #Sundowns #DownsLive #CAFCLFinal pic.twitter.com/vfwXDkw24P &mdash; Mamelodi Sundowns FC (@Masandawana) October 15, 2016 Masandawana and the Egyptian giants are facing off to be crowned African club champions for 2015/2016. The second leg will be played in Alexandria, Egypt, on 21 October 2016. Sundowns have beaten Zamalek twice already in this year&rsquo;s tournament. The Pretoria team is bidding to join Orlando Pirates, which one South Africa&rsquo;s only Championship League title in 1995. Unreal scenes at the LMS, this is how we do it. Thank you Masandawana! pic.twitter.com/EWBfqJwoIQ &mdash; Mamelodi Sundowns FC (@Masandawana) October 15, 2016 (Edited by Masechaba Sefularo) JOHANNESBURG &ndash; Mamelodi Sundowns emerge victorious in the hotly contested match against Egypt&rsquo;s Zamalek at the Lucas Moripe Stadium in Pretoria on Saturday. Sundowns won by 3-0 against Zamalek in the first leg of the CAF Champions League final.&nbsp;#CAFCLFinal 